","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Apperley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English:","habitational name from Apperley in Deerhurst (Gloucestershire), which derives from Old English <i>apuldor</i> ‘apple-tree’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘open woodland’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Apperley was born in 1393, in Deerhurst, Gloucestershire, England, her father, Edward Apperley, was 27 and her mother, Mrs. Emma Apperley, was 23. She married Edward Brydges in 1409. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died on 14 November 1430, in her hometown, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1393–14 November 1430":"1393–14. november 1430","1393–1430":"1393–1430","1389–1436":"1389–1436","1389–1430":"1389–1430","1415–1469":"1415–1469","1415–1466":"1415–1466","1416–1442":"1416–1442","1419–Male":"1419–Surnud","1367–Male":"1367–Surnud","1371–Female":"1371–Surnud","14 November 1430":"14. november 1430","1393":"1393","1371":"1371","14 Nov 1430":"14. november 1430","1415":"1415","1469":"1469","1436":"1436","1367":"1367","1466":"1466","1389":"1389","about 1416":"umbes 141